import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Assume that 'df_data' is your DataFrame and 'Practical Power' is the target variable
df_data = pd.read_csv('wind_data.csv')

# Convert the 'datetime' column to pandas datetime object
df_data['datetime'] = pd.to_datetime(df_data['datetime'])

# Extracting year, month, day, hour and minute from datetime object
df_data['year'] = df_data['datetime'].dt.year
df_data['month'] = df_data['datetime'].dt.month
df_data['day'] = df_data['datetime'].dt.day
df_data['hour'] = df_data['datetime'].dt.hour
df_data['minute'] = df_data['datetime'].dt.minute

X = df_data[['Wheel height wind direction', 'Temperature', 'Air Pressure','month','day','humidity','Capacity', 'hour', 'minute']]
y = df_data['Practical Power']

# Split the data into training and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)

# Initialize and fit the model
model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predict the next 24 hours wind energy
# Assuming the test data represents the next 24 hours
predictions = model.predict(X_test)

# Plot the results
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(predictions, label='Predicted')
plt.plot(y_test.values, label='Actual')
plt.ylabel('Wind Energy')
plt.xlabel('Time')
plt.title('Random Forest model for 24-hour wind energy change')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

In [93]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import LSTM, Dense
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load and preprocess data
df_data = pd.read_csv('wind_data.csv')

# Convert the 'datetime' column to pandas datetime object
df_data['datetime'] = pd.to_datetime(df_data['datetime'])

# Extracting year, month, day, hour and minute from datetime object
df_data['year'] = df_data['datetime'].dt.year
df_data['month'] = df_data['datetime'].dt.month
df_data['day'] = df_data['datetime'].dt.day
df_data['hour'] = df_data['datetime'].dt.hour
df_data['minute'] = df_data['datetime'].dt.minute

# Prepare data
data = df_data[['Wheel height wind direction', 'Temperature', 'Air Pressure','month','day','humidity','Capacity', 'hour', 'minute', 'Practical Power']]

# Scale data to range (0, 1)
scaler = MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(0, 1))
data_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(data)

# Split into features (X) and target (y)
X = data_scaled[:, :-1]
y = data_scaled[:, -1]

# Reshape input to be 3D [samples, timesteps, features]
X = X.reshape((X.shape[0], 1, X.shape[1]))

# Split the data into training and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)

# Define the LSTM model
model = Sequential()
model.add(LSTM(50, return_sequences=True, input_shape=(X_train.shape[1], X_train.shape[2])))
model.add(LSTM(50))
model.add(Dense(1))

# Compile the LSTM model
model.compile(loss='mae', optimizer='adam')

# Fit the model
history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=50, batch_size=72, validation_data=(X_test, y_test), shuffle=False)

# Make predictions
predictions = model.predict(X_test)

# Rescale predictions back to original scale
predictions_rescaled = scaler.inverse_transform(np.concatenate([X_test.reshape(X_test.shape[0], X_test.shape[2]), predictions], axis=1))[:, -1]
y_test_rescaled = scaler.inverse_transform(np.concatenate([X_test.reshape(X_test.shape[0], X_test.shape[2]), y_test.reshape(-1, 1)], axis=1))[:, -1]

# Plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))

plt.plot(predictions_rescaled, label='Predicted')
plt.plot(y_test_rescaled, label='Actual')
plt.title('LSTM model for 24-hour wind energy change')
plt.xlabel('Time')
plt.ylabel('Wind Energy')
plt.ylim(11.5, 16.5)  # Setting y-axis limits
plt.legend()
plt.show()

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsRegressor
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Split the data
X1_train, X1_test, y1_train, y1_test = train_test_split(df_data[['Wheel height wind direction', 'Temperature', 'Air Pressure','month','day','humidity','Capacity']], df_data[ 'Practical Power'], test_size=0.25, random_state=42)

# Train the KNN model
knn = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=5)
knn.fit(X1_train, y1_train)

# Make predictions for the next 24 hours (assuming the test set represents the next 24 hours)
predictions = knn.predict(X1_test)

# Create a DataFrame to compare the actual vs predicted values
df_comparison = pd.DataFrame({'Actual': y1_test, 'Predicted': predictions})

# Reset index for the plot
df_comparison = df_comparison.reset_index(drop=True)


# Plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))

plt.plot(df_comparison['Predicted'], label='Predicted')

plt.plot(df_comparison['Actual'], label='Actual')



plt.title('KNN model for 24-hour wind energy change')
plt.xlabel('Time')
plt.ylabel('Wind Energy')
plt.ylim(11.5, 16.5)  # Setting y-axis limits
plt.legend()
plt.show()

from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_percentage_error

# Fit the Random Forest Regression model
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
rf_pred = rf.predict(X_test)

# Reporting metrics
mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, rf_pred)
rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, rf_pred))
mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_test, rf_pred)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, rf_pred)

print('MAE:', mae)
print('RMSE:', rmse)
print('MAPE:', mape)
print('R2 Score:', r2)

# Create scatter plot of true vs. predicted radiation
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.scatter(y_test, rf_pred, color='coral', linewidths=2, edgecolors='k')
plt.xlabel('True') 
plt.ylabel('Predicted') 
plt.title('Random Forest Regression Prediction Performance') 
plt.grid()

# Add regression line
m, b = np.polyfit(y_test, rf_pred, 1)
x = np.arange(y_test.min(), y_test.max(), 50)
plt.plot(x, m*x+b)

# Add a line for perfect predictions
x_l = np.linspace(0, 16, 1000)
plt.plot(x_l, x_l)

# Display metrics in the plot
plt.text(0.1, 0.9, f'MAE: {mae:.2f}', transform=plt.gca().transAxes)
plt.text(0.1, 0.85, f'RMSE: {rmse:.2f}', transform=plt.gca().transAxes)
plt.text(0.1, 0.8, f'MAPE: {mape:.2f}', transform=plt.gca().transAxes)
plt.text(0.1, 0.75, f'R2 Score: {r2:.2f}', transform=plt.gca().transAxes)

plt.show()

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsRegressor
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error, r2_score
import time
# Define KNN model with k=5
knn = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=5)

start = time.time()

# Train KNN model on training data
knn.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on test data
knn_pred = knn.predict(X_test)

end = time.time()

# Calculate Mean Squared Error (MSE)
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, knn_pred)

# Calculate Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE)
rmse = np.sqrt(mse)

# Calculate Mean Absolute Error (MAE)
mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, knn_pred)

# Calculate R2 Score
r2 = r2_score(y_test, knn_pred)

# Calculate Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE)
mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_test - knn_pred) / y_test)) * 100

# Report metrics
print('MSE:', mse)
print('RMSE:', rmse)
print('MAE:', mae)
print('MAPE:', mape)
print('R2 Score:', r2)
print('Time:', end - start)

# Create scatter plot of true Vs. predicted values
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.scatter(y_test, knn_pred, color='coral', linewidths=2, edgecolors='k')
plt.xlabel('True') 
plt.ylabel('Predicted') 
plt.title('KNN Regression Prediction Performance') 
plt.grid()

m, b = np.polyfit(y_test, knn_pred, 1)
x = np.arange(y_test.min(), y_test.max(), 50)
plt.plot(x, m*x + b)

x_l = np.linspace(0, 16, 1000)
plt.plot(x_l, x_l)
plt.show()
